metadata.name: PROCEDURAL ESSENCE #21
metadata.description:
Let's imagine an abstract generative piece inspired by the style of Piet Mondrian, but taken to new dimensions using the Hydra tool. In this work, the geometric essence and simplicity of Mondrian is fused with the complexity and dynamism of procedural generation.

The basis of the composition consists of blocks of pixels arranged in an orderly manner reminiscent of Mondrian's art. However, unlike the static works of the famous Dutch painter, these blocks of pixels do not remain static. They move, change size and rotate, giving a sensation of constant movement.

Mondrian's influence is also reflected in the horizontal and vertical lines that cross the composition. These lines provide an underlying structure, dividing the generative canvas into sections reminiscent of Mondrian's gridded paintings. However, like pixel blocks, these lines are not limited by static; They move, create dynamic patterns and break with the rigidity of the square and rectangle.

The introduction of a noise texture adds an intriguing dimension to the work. This noise texture overlays the blocks and lines, creating areas of tonal variation and visual distortion. The noise texture not only breaks the visual uniformity, but also provides a feeling of controlled chaos, balancing the geometric structure of the piece.

The most distinctive thing about this generative work is its ability to change its appearance with each output. The aspect ratio fluctuates, transforming the arrangement of blocks, lines and noise texture in each iteration. This constant variation provides a dynamic and captivating viewing experience.

The color palette is varied and vibrant, taking inspiration from Mondrian's signature primary and secondary colors. However, unlike traditional works, the colors here are not static. They blend and transition smoothly, creating fascinating visual effects and evoking a feeling of constant change.

by Daniel Oropeza
Generative Abstract NFT
Made with Hydra.

metadata.description:

There is little chance of a 'perfect' work of art. The small imperfections require reflection.¬†

The variation and randomness give the work some asymmetry, common in wabi-sabi esthetics. Because of a limited color palette and the simple shapes used,¬†the works keep their simplicity (another principle of wabi-sabi). The colors are reminiscent of the 70s and 80s. Some think that everything was better in the past. The trick is to enjoy the moment.

metadata.name: monogrid 1.1 CE #256
metadata.description:
Each monogrid artwork gets initialized with a start up algorithm that builds up a set of rectangles and fills them with pixels. There are two different styles, 'Pixel' and 'Line', to create the initial image.

There is a set of 16 animations at work. 4 noise based animations, 4 shifting animations, 4 modulo based animation and 4 reset animations, all run in parallel. Each animation selects a rectangle from the initial setup and edits the pixels in this area. The selection process runs independently and animations can overlap which results in a new style of animation.

monogrid 1.1 is based on the original series at https://monogrid.xyz, but there are no black/white versions included. The color palette is a mixture of one of 12 colors plus black or white.
The fragment shader has been updated in the way the 16 different animations get summed up. This version would appear more chaotic and organic.

monogrid 1.1 - Collectors Edition
Kim Asendorf, 2022

metadata.name: Composition #3 Patchwork Quilt #56
metadata.description:
Abstract, non-square(!) composition based on textural strokes and noise. There are a lot of possible combinations with all of the features! 50% chance of two different palette sets. 50% chance to have a brush textured background, and a 50% chance of it being horizontal or vertical. The quadtree rectangles are based on poisson disc sampling based on a simplex noise field. 90% of the compositions will be smaller boxes, and 10% will be large. For each box, there is a 10% chance that it will be oriented opposite of the rest.

metadata.name: MAGNETIK #219
metadata.description:
The output of MAGNETIK reminds me of what tornadoes do to our cities and buildings, yet I imagine the pieces that are about to break off and fly away to be made of metal foil and they do so because of a magnetic force that is pulling them away from where they belong‚Ä¶‚Ä®‚Ä®This one is also a charity run : ‚Ä®
- 20% of the primary sales will go directly to the Processing Foundation, 

- Remaining 80% will be donated to a group of individuals that raise money to buy computers for less fortunate architecture students in a university in the eastern part of Turkey. Please read the next paragraph for a detailed explanation

- I will decide what to do with the secondary sales later if there will be any.

About the majority (80%) of the donation : I decided that the donations should be done in a double-blind way, the donator does not know who they are donating to, and the receivers of the donation will not know from whom the donation is coming from, hence I will transfer the funds these individuals mentioned to act as a middle-step. I feel like this is a hard thing to provide a solid proof for, so I recommend if you have doubts and/or straight away do not trust me or this process, do not mint. I will only be able to provide proof of transfer of funds to a third-party. I trust the people I am sending the funds to, we have done this before (not to brag or anything) and I know that we are affecting younger people‚Äôs life in a good way. Also, I believe that the funds raised from this project alone will not be enough to buy one decent config. computer by itself, if it were so, I would have done it differently.‚Ä®‚Ä®About MAGNETIK : ‚Ä®
MAGNETIK plays on the idea of distorting and breaking grids by employing an illusion of fake 3D and tries to make the resulting composition look good with rhythm and color harmony.
 
- 21 palettes,
- 2 background modes : lights on / lights off,
- 3 grid types,
- plus some surprise features‚Ä¶

I encourage you to try and see the variations before minting :)‚Ä®‚Ä®2 of the grid types are based on https://gorillasun.de/blog/an-algorithm-for-irregular-grids by Ahmad Moussa ( https://twitter.com/gorillasu ) and used with his knowledge and kind permission.

gradient formulas are based on https://twitter.com/takawo/status/1505876107492720651?s=20&t=S9aU_oNYyjBieBcEmvUV-g
by Takawo Shunsuke ( https://twitter.com/takawo ) and used with his knowledge and kind permission.

Thank you all in advance and have a good day!

DISCLAIMER : I am not a good coder, I have tried to fix my past mistakes from my earlier projects to make some room for new mistakes :) I am hoping that there isn‚Äôt any huge bugs or anything left so you can enjoy your mint! Please hit me up if you have any concerns after minting and we can discuss a solution.

metadata.name: ARAUCO #82
metadata.description:
The Araucaria Araucana, also known as pew√©n, is a sacred tree for the Mapuche and an emblem of Chile. With an origin dating back 260 million years to the Triassic period, it is part of the oldest forests on the planet. These ancient trees are endangered due to logging, forest fires, and grazing.

ARAUCO is a tribute to araucarias and Mapuche iconography. Incorporating elements such as the Kultrung, the W√ºnelfe star, and the staggered cross Ng√ºmin, the work displays a typical landscape of southern Chile with the Andes Mountains in the background and the native forest.

metadata.name: PWTC #94
metadata.description:
PWTC (Play with tubes and circles) is an artistic exercise of creation by repetition. Composed with only 2 simple shapes and a limited color palette, the beauty of the patterns generated comes from the repetition and random ordering made possible by the junction of artistic thought in intersection with code.

#Main Features

* ORIENTATION ‚Äì 60% horizontal; 40% vertical
* TEXTURE ‚Äì 50% point; 30% scribble; 20% scratch
* GREY SCALE ‚Äì 5% chance
* INVERT ‚Äì 2,5% chance
